  "notes": "Middle English (~1100–1500 CE). Post-Norman Conquest (~1066); models Chaucerian Late ME (~1380–1400). NORMAN FRENCH SUPERSTRATE: /v/ phonemicised; /dʒ/ extended via French; /ʒ/ enters (vision, pleasure) in late ME. OE diphthongs simplified: ea→ɛ, eo→e. OE front rounded /y/ → /i/ (lost). GREAT VOWEL SHIFT beginning ~1400–1700: long vowels raised/diphthongised. Dialect continuum: Northern (Scots), Midland (Chaucer), Southern. Major texts: Canterbury Tales (Chaucer), Piers Plowman, Sir Gawain and the Green Knight. Source: Hogg (1992), Fischer (2000).",
